<SiteLayout
  site="westmount"
  title="Best Canadian Brokerages (2026): Complete Comparison & Guide"
  description="The ultimate comparison of Canadian online brokerages in 2026. We review Wealthsimple, Questrade, IBKR, TD Direct, BMO, National Bank, and Qtrade."
  canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/canadian-brokerages-2026"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>The Best Canadian Brokerages for 2026</h1>
      <p>A comprehensive analysis of Wealthsimple, Questrade, IBKR, Big Bank Brokerages, and more.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <p>Investing in the Canadian stock market has never been more accessible, yet choosing the right platform can be an overwhelming task. With an array of discount brokerages, big bank trading platforms, and zero-commission disruptors, investors are spoiled for choice. However, the wrong choice can lead to significant friction, excessive fees, and suboptimal portfolio management over time.</p>

      <p>In this extensive guide, we will break down the absolute best Canadian brokerages for 2026, comparing their fee structures, account types, trading platforms, research tools, and overall value propositions. We will cover Wealthsimple, Questrade, Interactive Brokers (IBKR), TD Direct Investing, BMO InvestorLine, National Bank Direct Brokerage, and Qtrade. Our goal is to equip you with the deep knowledge required to select the brokerage that aligns perfectly with your financial goals, whether you are a complete novice buying your first index fund or a seasoned options trader utilizing complex margin strategies.</p>

      <h2>The Evolution of the Canadian Brokerage Landscape</h2>
      <p>Historically, Canadian investors were subjected to some of the highest trading commissions in the developed world. Not too long ago, paying $29.95 per trade was the industry standard, making it incredibly difficult for retail investors with smaller portfolios to build wealth efficiently without having large chunks of their capital eroded by fees. The landscape began shifting with the introduction of discount brokerages like Questrade, which significantly lowered the barrier to entry with deep discount commissions and, crucially, free ETF purchases.</p>
      <p>The real paradigm shift occurred in recent years with the arrival of zero-commission trading, spearheaded in Canada by Wealthsimple. This forced traditional institutions to re-evaluate their pricing models, leading to responses like National Bank Direct Brokerage eliminating commissions entirely for stocks and ETFs. Meanwhile, sophisticated international players like Interactive Brokers expanded their Canadian presence, offering institutional-grade tools and incredibly low margin rates to the retail market.</p>
      <p>Today, in 2026, the market is highly segmented. We have platforms optimized for passive investors, platforms designed for active day traders, and legacy bank platforms attempting to retain clients through ecosystem integration and premium research offerings. Understanding these segments is key to making your choice.</p>

      <h2>Wealthsimple: The Zero-Commission Pioneer</h2>
      <p>Wealthsimple fundamentally changed the Canadian investing landscape when it launched Wealthsimple Trade (now integrated into the broader Wealthsimple app). It introduced the concept of zero-commission stock and ETF trading to a market that desperately needed it. For the vast majority of new investors, and those whose strategy revolves around buying and holding Canadian-listed ETFs and equities, Wealthsimple remains a top-tier choice.</p>
      <p><strong>Fee Structure:</strong> Wealthsimple's core value proposition is zero commissions on all CAD-denominated stock and ETF trades. There are no account minimums, no inactivity fees, and no ECN (Electronic Communication Network) fees, which are often hidden costs at other discount brokerages. The platform makes its money primarily on foreign exchange (FX) fees when you trade US-listed securities. By default, Wealthsimple charges a 1.5% currency conversion fee on both the buy and sell sides of US trades.</p>
      <p><strong>USD Accounts and Premium Tiers:</strong> Recognizing the limitation of their forced-FX model, Wealthsimple introduced premium tiers. The Plus tier (currently $10/month) allows investors to hold USD in their accounts, eliminating the 1.5% fee on every single US trade (though you still pay it when initially converting CAD to USD, or vice versa). For investors with larger portfolios (Premium and Generation tiers), USD accounts are included for free, along with other perks. If you want to dive deeper into how Wealthsimple compares to its main rival, check out our detailed <a href="/wealthsimple-vs-questrade">Wealthsimple vs Questrade</a> comparison, or read our full <a href="/wealthsimple-review-2026">Wealthsimple Review 2026</a>.</p>
      <p><strong>Best For:</strong> Beginners, passive index investors buying Canadian ETFs (like XEQT or VGRO), and anyone who values a sleek, mobile-first, incredibly simple user interface. If you are looking for the absolute <a href="/best-brokerage-for-beginners">best brokerage for beginners</a>, Wealthsimple is often the undisputed winner.</p>

      <h2>Questrade: The Established Discount King</h2>
      <p>Questrade has been a dominant force in the independent discount brokerage space for over two decades. They built their reputation by drastically undercutting the big banks and introducing the immensely popular "free ETF purchases" feature. While they face steeper competition now than ever before, Questrade remains a highly versatile and reliable platform for a wide range of investors.</p>
      <p><strong>Fee Structure:</strong> Questrade's hallmark feature is free ETF purchases (you only pay a few pennies in ECN fees). Selling ETFs, as well as buying and selling individual stocks, incurs a commission of 1 cent per share, with a minimum of $4.95 and a maximum of $9.95. For investors deploying regular contributions into a passive ETF portfolio, the costs are virtually non-existent on the buy side, making it an excellent platform for dollar-cost averaging.</p>
      <p><strong>Account Types and Tools:</strong> Questrade offers almost every account type imaginable: RRSPs, TFSAs, RESPs, LIRAs, Margin accounts, and corporate accounts. Their trading platforms range from a simple web interface to Questrade Edge, a downloadable desktop platform designed for more active traders. Crucially, Questrade allows you to hold USD in your registered and non-registered accounts without a monthly fee. This, combined with their support for Norbert's Gambit (a strategy to convert currency cheaply), makes them a strong contender. See our <a href="/questrade-vs-ibkr">Questrade vs IBKR</a> guide for a breakdown of how they compare for active traders.</p>
      <p><strong>Best For:</strong> Balanced investors who want the ability to buy ETFs for free, hold USD natively without monthly fees, access a wide variety of account types, and perform Norbert's Gambit. They sit comfortably in the middle ground between the simplicity of Wealthsimple and the complexity of Interactive Brokers.</p>

      <h2>Interactive Brokers (IBKR): The Powerhouse</h2>
      <p>Interactive Brokers (IBKR) is a global brokerage behemoth that has made significant inroads into the Canadian market. They are fundamentally different from Wealthsimple and Questrade; IBKR is built from the ground up for active traders, institutional clients, and highly sophisticated retail investors. The learning curve is steep, but the capabilities are unmatched.</p>
      <p><strong>Fee Structure:</strong> IBKR offers two main pricing tiers in Canada: Tiered and Fixed. Tiered pricing can be incredibly cheap, often resulting in commissions of less than a dollar for small stock or ETF trades. Options trading is also significantly cheaper than almost any Canadian competitor. However, the most profound advantage IBKR holds is its currency conversion. IBKR allows users to convert currency at the spot rate with a nominal flat fee (typically around $2 USD). This completely eliminates the need for complex workarounds like Norbert's Gambit. For anyone trading significant volumes of US equities, this is a game-changer. Read our dedicated guide on <a href="/interactive-brokers-canada">Interactive Brokers Canada</a> for an in-depth look at their fee mechanics.</p>
      <p><strong>Margin and Tools:</strong> IBKR is famous for offering the lowest margin rates in the industry. If you plan on using leverage, IBKR is almost always the mathematically correct choice. Their flagship trading platform, Trader Workstation (TWS), is overwhelmingly complex for a beginner but immensely powerful for an experienced trader, offering advanced charting, algorithmic trading capabilities, and deep options analytics. We frequently recommend IBKR as the <a href="/best-brokerage-for-usd">best brokerage for USD trading</a> due to their spot-rate conversions.</p>
      <p><strong>Best For:</strong> Active traders, options traders, investors utilizing margin, individuals who frequently trade US or international equities, and advanced users who demand institutional-grade tools and execution.</p>

      <h2>TD Direct Investing: The Premium Bank Brokerage</h2>
      <p>When it comes to the "Big Six" Canadian banks, TD Direct Investing is widely considered the gold standard for brokerage platforms. It is the largest online brokerage in Canada by assets under administration, and it leverages TD's massive resources to offer a premium, albeit expensive, investing experience.</p>
      <p><strong>Fee Structure:</strong> This is where TD Direct Investing struggles to compete with the independent discount brokers. They charge a flat $9.99 per trade for stocks and ETFs. There are no free ETF purchases. For an investor making frequent, small contributions, these fees will cause devastating drag on portfolio returns over time. They also charge a quarterly maintenance fee for small accounts, though this can be waived by setting up regular deposits or holding multiple TD products.</p>
      <p><strong>Research and Platform:</strong> Where TD shines is in its ecosystem and research. The WebBroker platform is highly regarded for its stability, intuitive design, and integration with everyday TD banking. Furthermore, TD provides clients with access to an incredible wealth of institutional research, including Morningstar reports, Argus analysis, and TD's own proprietary equity research. For investors managing substantial portfolios who value having all their financial services under one roof and utilizing top-tier research, the higher trading fees may be justifiable. To understand when paying these premiums makes sense, explore our <a href="/td-direct-vs-discount">TD Direct vs Discount Brokers</a> analysis.</p>
      <p><strong>Best For:</strong> Existing TD bank customers who value convenience, high-net-worth investors who trade infrequently in large blocks, and investors who heavily utilize institutional research to make their decisions.</p>

      <h2>National Bank Direct Brokerage: The Big Bank Disruptor</h2>
      <p>National Bank Direct Brokerage (NBDB) sent shockwaves through the Canadian financial industry when it became the first (and so far, only) major Canadian bank brokerage to eliminate commissions entirely on Canadian and US stocks and ETFs. They essentially adopted the Wealthsimple pricing model but applied it to a full-service bank platform.</p>
      <p><strong>Fee Structure:</strong> $0 commissions on stocks and ETFs. This is a massive advantage over TD, BMO, RBC, CIBC, and Scotia. However, like TD, they do have an annual administration fee of $100 for accounts under $20,000, though this is waived for young investors (under 30), students, and active traders.</p>
      <p><strong>The Catch:</strong> While stock and ETF trades are free, NBDB's platform is generally considered less polished than TD WebBroker or Questrade. They also have higher fees for options trading compared to IBKR, and their currency conversion fees (if you don't use Norbert's Gambit) are standard bank rates. Nevertheless, the ability to get zero-commission trading while maintaining the security and account variety of a major bank makes NBDB a highly compelling hybrid option.</p>
      <p><strong>Best For:</strong> Investors who want zero commissions but prefer the stability of a big bank, and those who want to hold USD accounts without the monthly fees associated with Wealthsimple Plus.</p>

      <h2>BMO InvestorLine: A Solid Contender with a Unique Niche</h2>
      <p>BMO InvestorLine is another major bank offering that falls somewhere between TD's premium model and NBDB's zero-commission model. While their standard commission is also $9.99 per trade, they have attempted to compete by offering a curated list of over 80 commission-free ETFs. This list includes many popular BMO ETFs (like ZSP, ZAG) and some iShares products.</p>
      <p><strong>Platform and Features:</strong> BMO's platform is robust and offers excellent research tools. They are also highly accommodating of Norbert's Gambit, allowing users to journal shares online without having to call a representative (a major pain point with some other brokers). If your investment strategy aligns perfectly with the ETFs on their free list, BMO InvestorLine can be a very cost-effective way to keep your investments integrated with your daily banking.</p>
      <p><strong>Best For:</strong> Existing BMO clients, investors whose strategy relies heavily on the specific ETFs included in BMO's commission-free list, and those who frequently perform Norbert's Gambit.</p>

      <h2>Qtrade Direct Investing: The Customer Service Champion</h2>
      <p>Qtrade (not to be confused with Questrade) is often overlooked in broader discussions, but it consistently ranks at or near the top of independent brokerage surveys for customer satisfaction and website usability. Owned by Aviso Wealth (which is backed by credit unions), Qtrade offers a highly refined user experience.</p>
      <p><strong>Fee Structure:</strong> Qtrade's standard commission is $8.75 per trade, making it slightly cheaper than the big banks but more expensive than Questrade. However, they offer a list of over 100 commission-free ETFs (similar to BMO) and reduce their standard commission to $6.95 for active traders or those with larger portfolios.</p>
      <p><strong>The Qtrade Advantage:</strong> Qtrade's primary selling points are its exceptional customer service, highly intuitive platform design, and excellent portfolio analysis tools. For investors who are willing to pay a slight premium over Questrade in exchange for superior support and a less clunky interface, Qtrade is an excellent alternative. It is particularly popular among credit union members, as it often integrates seamlessly with their banking portals.</p>

      <h2>How to Choose the Right Brokerage for You</h2>
      <p>Choosing the right brokerage is not a one-size-fits-all decision. To make the best choice, you need to clearly define your investor profile. Consider the following factors:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Trading Frequency:</strong> If you buy stocks or ETFs every week with a portion of your paycheck, high commissions will destroy your returns. You must prioritize Wealthsimple, Questrade (for ETFs), or National Bank. If you make two large trades a year, the $9.99 fee at TD matters much less.</li>
        <li><strong>Asset Allocation:</strong> Are you buying only Canadian-listed ETFs (like XEQT)? Wealthsimple is perfect. Are you building a portfolio of individual US tech stocks? You need a platform that handles USD efficiently, like IBKR or a brokerage where you can easily perform Norbert's Gambit (Questrade, NBDB, BMO).</li>
        <li><strong>Account Types Required:</strong> Do you need a Spousal RRSP, an RESP, or a corporate account? Wealthsimple has limited support for complex account structures compared to Questrade, IBKR, or the big banks.</li>
        <li><strong>Need for Research and Tools:</strong> Do you rely on the brokerage for stock screeners, analyst reports, and real-time level 2 data? The big banks and IBKR excel here, while Wealthsimple provides the bare minimum.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>To help you model out exactly how these fees will impact your specific portfolio size and trading frequency over time, we highly recommend utilizing our <a href="/brokerage-fee-calculator">brokerage fee calculator</a>. This tool will project your annual costs across all major platforms based on your unique inputs.</p>

      <h2>Conclusion: Our Top Picks for 2026</h2>
      <p>While the "best" brokerage is subjective, the current landscape allows us to make strong recommendations based on specific use cases. For the absolute beginner and the dedicated passive investor buying Canadian-listed broad market index funds, <strong>Wealthsimple</strong> remains our top recommendation due to its zero-friction, zero-commission environment. For the active trader, the options enthusiast, and anyone with a large USD portfolio, <strong>Interactive Brokers (IBKR)</strong> is unmatched in its pricing and capability. And for the investor who wants a balanced approach—the ability to buy ETFs for free while maintaining full control over USD accounts and complex account types—<strong>Questrade</strong> continues to be a highly reliable workhorse.</p>
      <p>Take the time to evaluate your needs, understand the fee structures, and don't be afraid to utilize multiple brokerages if it serves your strategy. A common and highly effective setup is using Wealthsimple for a TFSA filled with Canadian index funds, and IBKR for an RRSP dedicated to US equities.</p>

    </div>
  </div>

